---
/**
 * Error Reading Cheat Sheet - HAP's Learning Lab: Living in the Terminal
 *
 * A standalone reference page for reading and triaging errors.
 * Signal vs noise, what to copy, what to skip.
 * Date-stamped March 2026 — this landscape changes fast.
 */

import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';

const introContent = `
    <p><strong>This is my cheat sheet for reading errors.</strong> When I started out, every red line in the terminal felt like a personal attack. Now I know that the error message is trying to help me — I just had to learn how to listen. Prof. Teeters taught me a system, and it changed everything.</p>
    <p class="mt-1">Most of what I know about reading errors came from Station 6, where I learned to be the human architect who triages before asking for help. 🟠</p>
`;
---

<MainLayout
    title="Reading Errors | HAP's Learning Lab"
    description="HAP's cheat sheet for reading error messages — signal vs noise, error triage, and what to copy to your AI agent."
    headerTitle="HAP's Learning Lab"
    headerSubtitle="Reading Errors"
    avatarImage="https://res.cloudinary.com/cynthia-teeters/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,w_200,c_limit/v1/hap-w-bug_fztbl6.jpg"
    avatarAlt="HAP robot debugging code with magnifying glass"
    introContent={introContent}
    showNavigation={false}
    footerReminder="The error message is not the enemy. It is the first clue."
>

    <!--
    HAP Educational Content © 2026 Cynthia Teeters. All rights reserved.
    HyBit A. ProtoBot (HAP) character and the apprentice learning methodology are proprietary educational innovations.
    -->

    <div class="intro-box">
        <p><strong>Date-stamped: March 2026.</strong> Error formats change as tools update. The triage method stays the same: read the first line, identify the category, gather context, then ask for help.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 1: Signal vs Noise
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>Signal vs Noise</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">The first error is usually the cause. Everything after is often consequence. I learned from Prof. Teeters to read the first red line before panicking.</p>

            <div class="intro-box">
                <p><strong>The rule:</strong> When you see a wall of red text, do not scroll to the bottom. Scroll to the <em>top</em>. The first error triggered everything else. Fix that one, and half the others may disappear on their own.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 2: Vite and Build Errors
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>Vite and Build Errors</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">Build tools like Vite produce cascading errors. The real problem is at the top — the rest is noise.</p>

            <div class="tips-container">
                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">1</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>The Pattern</h3>
                        <p>Lines 1-3 are the real error. Lines 4-20 are cascade. When I was practicing, I used to copy all 200 lines to my agent. Prof. Teeters stopped me and said: "Give it the first three lines. That is where the answer lives."</p>
                        <CodeBlock code={`# What the terminal shows:
error: Could not resolve "./components/Headr.astro"
  at src/pages/index.astro:3:25
  ... 17 more lines of stack trace you can ignore`} lang="text" />
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">2</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>What to Copy</h3>
                        <p>Copy the first 3 lines to your agent, not all 200. The file name and line number are the signal. The stack trace is noise — unless your agent specifically asks for it.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 3: Browser Console Errors
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>Browser Console Errors</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">The browser console groups errors into categories. Identify the category first, then ask the right questions.</p>

            <div class="analysis-grid analysis-grid--two-col">
                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>SyntaxError</h3>
                    <p>Something is written wrong — a missing bracket, a typo, an extra comma. The browser cannot even parse the file.</p>
                    <CodeBlock code={`Uncaught SyntaxError: Unexpected token '}'
  at script.js:42`} lang="text" />
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>ReferenceError</h3>
                    <p>You used a name that does not exist. Usually a typo or a missing import.</p>
                    <CodeBlock code={`Uncaught ReferenceError: contaner is not defined
  at script.js:15`} lang="text" />
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>Network Error</h3>
                    <p>A fetch or resource load failed. Check the URL, check if the server is running, check your internet connection.</p>
                    <CodeBlock code={`GET http://localhost:4321/api/data 404 (Not Found)`} lang="text" />
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>CORS Error</h3>
                    <p>The browser blocked a cross-origin request. This is a server configuration issue, not a code bug.</p>
                    <CodeBlock code={`Access to fetch at 'https://api.example.com'
from origin 'http://localhost:4321'
has been blocked by CORS policy`} lang="text" />
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="intro-box">
                <p><strong>Three questions to ask yourself:</strong> What file? What line? What did I expect vs what happened? If you can answer those three, you have enough context to ask your agent for help.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 4: Terminal Errors
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>Terminal Errors</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">Terminal errors are usually short and direct. The message tells you exactly what went wrong — once you know the vocabulary.</p>

            <div class="tips-container">
                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">?</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>command not found</h3>
                        <p>The tool is not installed, or it is not in your PATH. This was tricky for me too — I kept thinking I had broken something, but it just meant I needed to install the tool first.</p>
                        <CodeBlock code={`zsh: command not found: netlify
# Fix: npm install -g netlify-cli`} lang="bash" />
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">!</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>permission denied</h3>
                        <p>You do not have the right permissions to run this command or access this file. Do not just add <code>sudo</code> without understanding why.</p>
                        <CodeBlock code={`bash: ./script.sh: Permission denied
# Check permissions first:
ls -la script.sh`} lang="bash" />
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">/</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>No such file or directory</h3>
                        <p>Wrong path. Always run <code>pwd</code> first to confirm where you are. I learned from Prof. Teeters: most "file not found" errors are really "I am in the wrong directory" errors.</p>
                        <CodeBlock code={`cat: src/index.html: No such file or directory
# First check:
pwd
ls src/`} lang="bash" />
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 5: What to Give the Agent
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>What to Give the Agent</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">When I ask my AI agent for help with an error, I give it these five things. Prof. Teeters called this "context engineering for debugging."</p>

            <div class="tips-container">
                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">1</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>Your OS and shell</h3>
                        <p>"I am on macOS using zsh" or "I am on Windows using Git Bash." This changes what commands and paths look like.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">2</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>The exact command you ran</h3>
                        <p>Copy-paste it. Do not paraphrase. "I ran npm something" is not helpful. <code>npm run build</code> is.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">3</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>The exact error (first 3-5 lines)</h3>
                        <p>Copy the first 3-5 lines of the error output. Not the whole thing — the signal, not the noise.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">4</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>What you expected to happen</h3>
                        <p>"I expected the dev server to start" or "I expected the file to be created in src/." This helps the agent understand the gap between expectation and reality.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tip-card">
                    <div class="tip-number">5</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>What you already know about the project</h3>
                        <p>"This is an Astro project" or "I just ran npm install." Context about the project helps the agent narrow down the problem fast.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         SECTION 6: What NOT to Do
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>What NOT to Do</h2>
            <p class="mb-2">I made all of these mistakes. More than once. 🟠</p>

            <div class="analysis-grid">
                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>Do not paste 200 lines of output</h3>
                    <p>Your agent will drown in noise. The first 3-5 lines contain the answer. The rest is cascade. I used to dump everything and wonder why the agent gave confused responses.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>Do not say "it doesn't work"</h3>
                    <p>That tells the agent nothing. What command did you run? What happened? What did you expect? "It doesn't work" is the least helpful thing you can type.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>Do not skip context</h3>
                    <p>Your agent cannot see your screen. It does not know your OS, your shell, your project structure, or what you just tried. The five items above are the minimum. Without them, the agent is guessing.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Back to stations
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section" style="text-align: center;">
        <p><a href="/">← Back to Learning Lab Hub</a></p>
    </section>

    <img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/cynthia-teeters/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,w_100,c_limit/v1/hap-waving_dgzacg.jpg" alt="HAP waving goodbye" width="100" height="100" loading="lazy" decoding="async" style="display: block; margin: 1rem auto;">

</MainLayout>
